08311nam a22011295i 9783035608236DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162017sz     fo  d z      eng d  a97830356082367 a10.1515/97830356082362doi  a(DE-B1597)463849  a(OCoLC)979688416  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aszcCH 4aNA958b.R473 2017 7aARC0050802bisacsh04a724.622300aEast West Central :bRe-building Europe, 1950-1990. nVolume 2, pRe-Scaling the Environment ; New Landscapes of Design, 1960-1980 /ced. by Ákos Moravánszky, Karl R. Kegler. 1aBasel : bBirkhäuser, c[2016] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEast West Central ;vVolume 200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword. East West Central: Re-Building Europe -- tIntroduction. On Systems and System Change -- tI. Technology: New Scales and Projects -- tZooming In: The Powers of Scale, 1960–1980 -- tThe Choreography of the Console: Electronic Environments and their Operators -- tRittel’s Riddles: Design Education and “Democratic” Planning in the Age of Information -- tNested Utopias: GEAM’s Large-Scale Designs -- tOn Bees and Bolts: Školka SIAL – An Architects’ Commune in Czechoslovakia -- tII. Planning, Design and Territory -- tLe Corbusier’s “Geo-Architecture” and the Emergence of Territorial Aesthetics -- tProjective Geographies Between East and West -- tTowards the Functional Society: Paradigm Shifts in the Regional Planning of West and East Germany -- tVacationing within the Walls. The Design and Development of Holiday Resorts in the GDR -- tUrbanism and Academia: Teaching Urban Design in the East -- tIII. Practices and Agencies -- tArchitectural Intelligence and Scarcity-Driven Design in the 1960s Yugoslavia -- tFrom New Empiricism to Structuralism. The Swedish National Board of Public Building (KBS) -- tCourtyards, Corners, Streetfronts: Re-Imagining Mass Housing Areas in Tallinn -- t“Complex Projects”: Landscape Architecture as the Integrating Discipline -- tUIA, R. Buckminster Fuller, and the Architectural Consequences of “Total Environment” -- tNew Agencies: Convergent Frameworks of Research and Architectural Design -- tAppendix -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom 1960–1980, both eastern and western Europe experienced a construction boom of new dimensions. Cybernetics, the science of planning, and sociology, as well as the new possibilities offered by technology and production, paved the way to large-scale processes and systems in architecture and urban design, which favored technocratic and utopian concepts. Increasingly, architects and planners saw themselves as designers of comprehensive infrastructure and mega-structures in a technology-focused world. The authors assesses these developments on the back of a knowledge transfer between East and West. It confirms a change in attitude that can still be felt today – recession, social changes, and environmental problems led to criticism of the then contemporary concepts of modernity.  aVon 1960 bis 1980 erlebten Ost-und Westeuropa eine Bauproduktion von bis dahin unbekanntem Ausmaß. Kybernetik, Planungswissenschaft und Soziologie sowie neue Möglichkeiten von Technologie und Produktion eröffneten in Architektur und Raumplanung ein Denken in Prozessen, Systemen und großen Maßstäben, das technokratische und utopische Konzepte begünstigte. Architekten und Planer verstanden sich zunehmend als Gestalter umfassender Infra- und Megastrukturen einer technisierten Lebenswelt. Das internationale Autorenteam behandelt diese Entwicklungen vor dem Hintergrund des Wissenstransfers zwischen Ost und West. Es konstatiert einen bis heute nachwirkenden Umschwung: Rezession, gesellschaftliche Umbrüche und Umweltprobleme führten zur Kritik an bisherigen Konzeptionen von Modernität.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArchitecture and societyzEurope. 0aArchitecturexHistoryx20th centuryxEurope. 0aArchitecturexTechnological innovationsxEuropexEuropexHistory. 0aArchitecturexTechnological innovationszEurope. 0aArchitecturezEuropexHistoryy20th century. 4aArchitectural History. 4aArchitekturgeschichte. 4aEuropa. 4aEurope. 4aNachkriegsmoderne. 4aPostwar Architecture. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh1 aBaum, Mirko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlagojević, Ljiljana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBujas, Piotr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrowley, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCupers, Kenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemchenko, Igor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscher, Cornelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGzowska, Alicja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKalpakci, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKegler, Karl R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKegler, Karl R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKurg, Andres, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLange, Torsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeggyesi, Tamás, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoravánszky, Ákos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoravánszky, Ákos, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSarkis, Hashim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc